## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
complexity
## Location
src/tool_intercept.rs:135-149 (has_pending_tool_calls), src/tool_intercept.rs:153-180 (has_complete_block)
## Violation
Both methods iterate every entry in `SHORTHAND_TOOLS` (9 entries) and call `String::contains` (a full O(N) scan of the buffer) twice per entry, plus a `contains("<invoke name=\"")`. That is up to 19 buffer scans per call. These are called on every streaming push from the SSE loop and again from `extract_all_tool_calls`'s `while self.has_complete_block()` driver (line 251). For an N-byte buffer accumulated over K pushes, total cost is O(K * 19 * N), i.e. quadratic in the response length.

```rust
for tool in Self::SHORTHAND_TOOLS {
    let open_tag = format!("<{tool}>");
    let open_tag_with_attr = format!("<{tool} ");
    if self.buffer.contains(&open_tag) || self.buffer.contains(&open_tag_with_attr) {
        return true;
    }
}
```

Plus `format!` allocates a fresh String per tool per call. For a long response the GC pressure is substantial.

## Mandated refactor
Build the tag strings once as `const`s (or `LazyLock<Vec<&'static str>>`). Compile a single Aho-Corasick matcher (or use the `memchr` crate) for the full pattern set. Even simpler: maintain a `scan_offset` field that records how far into the buffer the last scan went, and only re-scan from that point forward.
